Compatibility Determination Use: Refuge Name: Mosquito Control Salinas River National Wildlife Refuge
Establishing and Acquisition Authority: Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918, as amended (16 U.S. 703Â­712) Refuge Purpose(s): "Particular value in carrying out the national migratory bird management program" (USC Sec. 6676) National Wildlife Refuge System Mission: The mission of the National Wildlife Refuge System is "to administer a national network of lands and waters for the conservation, management, and where appropriate, restoration of the fish, wildlife and plant resources and their habitats within the United States for the benefit of present and future generations of Americans."
Description of Use(s): Three mosquito species are typically found at the Refuge (Ochlerotatus washinoi, Culiseta inornata, and Culex tarsalis); the Northern Salinas Valley Mosquito Abatement District (NSVMAD) has been conducting mosquito control at the Refuge for many years.
NSVMAD uses a stepped approach for mosquito control at the Refuge.
The first two steps utilize biorationals (Bti and methoprene).
However, depending on conditions (weather, water temperature, etc.) application of biocontrols is not always effective.
As a last resort, Golden Bear 1111 oil, a petroleum distillate, is applied.
Material selection is based on efficacy, instar, water temperature, and species of mosquito.
Each of these three materials is described in more detail below.
Bacillus thuringiensis israelensis - Bti is primarily used to control the early stages of immature mosquitoes.
Factors that influence the success of control using Bti are temperature, pH, salinity, density of vegetative cover, organic content of the water and larval stage and density.
Bti can be used for late stage immature mosquitoes, but shows decreased effectiveness, especially with the marsh mosquitoes.
Bti has no effect on the pupal or adult stage.
This larvicide is very specific, affecting only mosquitoes, blackflies and a few species of midges.
This larvicide is used in liquid and granular formulations.
Altosid (Methoprene) - Altosid, an insect growth regulator, is used to control late stage mosquito larvae.
Factors that affect successful application of Altosid are organic content of the water, aquatic microorganism density, density of vegetative cover and mosquito larval density.
UV light does break down Altosid, limiting its effective life in the water to three to five days.
Larvae treated with Altosid are unable to emerge from their pupal cases.
This larvicide is also very specific, affecting only mosquitoes, fleas and a few species of midges.
This larvicide is used in liquid, briquet and pellet formulations.
Golden Bear 1111 - When pupae are found, Golden Bear 1111 is used, as it is the only effective control agent available to prevent adult mosquito emergence.
The District
minimizes the use of this larvicide as much as possible because of its affects to non-target air breathing invertebrates.
GB-1111 (Golden Bear Oil) is used extensively as a larvicide by California Mosquito Abatement Districts (MAD) and it has been recommended by MAD for use on National Wildlife Refuges as a component of an integrated pest control formula for mosquito suppression.
GB-1111 is a petroleum distillate that is used as a lastresort larvicide when the larvae pupate before mosquito abatement personnel can treat the site with other materials.
There are few published studies of the non-target effects of GB1111 and the product label warns that "GB-1111 is toxic to fish and other aquatic organisms."
Since the avian embryo is contained in a virtually closed system, it is subjected to a situation environmentally similar to a fish in a small pond, with onlylimited recourse to protect itself from exposure to xenobiotics including petroleum compounds, pesticides, and industrial effluents.
Certain chemicals that have been toxic to fish have also proven to be quite toxic to bird embryos.
Albers and Heinz (1983) previously reported on a petroleum derived mosquito larvicide, FLIT-MLO (a straightchain or branched alkane product), that was toxic to mallard embryos when applied externally to eggs at three times the maximum recommended application rate.
GB-1111 is a cycloalkane product, hence toxicity of the hydrocarbons should be greater than those of FLIT-MLO.
Treatment is conducted almost exclusively by aerial application, but on rare occasions, when the treatment area is small, spraying is done by hand.
Aerial applications are made using a helicopter flown at an altitude of 5Â­10 feet at an airspeed of 55 mph.
Swath width is 66 feet, so several passes are made.
Treatment duration is approximately 15Â­20 minutes.
Mosquito control applications can be expected to occur any time between November and June, depending on environmental conditions.
Mosquito control typically occurs from December through April in the saline pond and salt marsh habitat on the Refuge.
This area is flooded during winter rains and winter high tides, resulting in a potential mosquito breeding site with an area of approximately 100 acres.
Mosquito populations are related to precipitation amounts.
In years when rainfall is below normal, mosquito populations are low and control is reduced or nonexistent.
Conversely, when rainfall is above normal, mosquito populations are larger and mosquito control is increased.
For example, between 1988 and 1991, rainfall was below normal and no mosquito control was conducted at the Refuge.
In the last six years, however, mosquito control applications occurred 2Â­4 times per year.
Availability of Resources: Adequate funding and staff exist to manage for mosquito control at the Salinas River National Wildlife Refuge.
Anticipated Impacts of the Use(s): Endangered and Threatened Species: Human activity can have adverse impacts on rare shore-nesting birds, especially during nesting and feeding activities.
The western snowy plover (Charadrius alexandrinus nivosus) (federally listed as threatened) is of primary
concern to the Refuge.
The Service strives to provide optimum breeding conditions for the western snowy plover.
However, in recent years, the number of breeding snowy plovers on the Refuge, and throughout the species' range, has decreased significantly as a result of adverse weather conditions on their wintering grounds and heavy predation by native and nonnative wildlife.
Although current levels of public use are low, human activity in the dunes and beaches during the snowy plover breeding season has the potential to adversely affect plover reproductive success.
Western snowy plovers utilize the entire beach profile, from the foredune through the coastal strand into the intertidal zone (between mean low tide and mean high tide lines) for breeding and foraging.
In addition, Point Reyes Bird Observatory has documented adult snowy plovers bringing chicks to the saline pond area to brood, as this area provides excellent cover and a good food source.
The most commonly used brooding site in the area is also located on the Refuge, at the mouth of the Salinas River.
The California brown pelican (Pelecanus occidentalis californicus) also utilizes the lagoon at the mouth of the Salinas River, as well as islands near the rivermouth, and portions of the beach strand as roosting sites, particularly from April through December.
Other federally listed species at the Refuge include: Smith's blue butterfly (Euphilotes enoptes smithi) and the Monterey gilia (Gilia tenuiflora ssp. arenaria) (federally listed as endangered); and the Monterey spineflower (Chorizanthe pungens var. pungens) (federally listed as threatened).
Mosquito Control personnel do not need to enter dune areas, so impacts on these species are not expected.
Wetlands and Migratory Birds: The saline pond and salt marsh habitats support a variety of migratory birds including waterfowl, shorebirds, raptors, terns, gulls, and wading birds.
The lagoon at the mouth of the Salinas River supports pelicans and waterfowl.
Shorebirds utilize the saline pond and rivermouth throughout the year.
Peak shorebird numbers occur during the spring (AprilÂ­May) and fall (SeptemberÂ­October) migration periods when hundreds of shorebirds are present at the saline pond and on the mudflats adjacent to the river.
A variety of wintering shorebirds utilize the pond area, including western sandpipers (Calidris mauri), American avocets (Recurvirostra americana), black-necked stilts (Himantopus mexicanus), dowitchers (Limnodromus spp.), sanderlings (Calidris alba), dunlin (C. alpina), and plovers.
In addition several species are known to nest in the pond area including the American avocet, black-necked stilt, and black skimmers (Rynchops niger).
The pond and rivermouth provide important habitat for migrating, wintering, and breeding waterfowl.
Daily winter waterfowl populations in the pond range from 50 to 500, depending on available water.
In addition, the Refuge pond is heavily used by dabbling ducks during spring migration as a stopover foraging and roosting site.
The rivermouth supports a large wintering population (500Â­2,000) of diving ducks.
Helicopter application is utilized because it is more effective than other methods and
prevents surface disturbance to sensitive marsh habitat.
However, helicopter application results in direct short-term disturbance of birds utilizing the saline pond, the salt marsh, and a portion of the Salinas River.
Disturbance during the breeding season may result in decreased breeding success.
Shorebirds tend to leave the area entirely during applications, potentially resulting in separation of chicks from adults if applications are made after mid-March, when shorebirds are nesting.
Helicopter applications during the nesting season may also result in eggs being blown from nests by rotor wash.
Pelicans, terns, and gulls roosting on the rivermouth flush when disturbed and then attempt to return to the roost.
However, repeated passes by the helicopter continue to disturb the birds.
This results in a majority of the pelicans leaving the Refuge.
Herons and egrets will flush from the pond and rivermouth areas when disturbed, moving upstream to undisturbed areas.
Waterfowl species react differently to the disturbance.
Dabblers such as pintails (Anas acuta) and mallards (Anas platyrhynchos) flush and leave the area.
Diving ducks such as ruddy ducks (Oxyura jamaicensis), buffleheads (Bucephala albeola), and scaups (Aythya spp.) will dive or move to avoid the disturbance but generally do not leave the Refuge.
In addition, there may be secondary impacts on birds utilizing the treated pond.
Birds feed on a wide variety of insects.
In particular, waterfowl and shorebirds utilize aquatic insects as a source of protein during spring migration.
Mosquito control methods can kill other invertebrate species in addition to mosquitoes.
As a result, the food source available in the pond is reduced for birds and other native wildlife.
Public Review and Comment: Public review and comment will be conducted concurrent with the public review and comment period for the CCP.
Determination (check one below): X Use is Not Compatible Use is Compatible With Following Stipulations
Stipulations Necessary to Ensure Compatibility: In order to allow mosquito abatement on the Refuge, the following measurers will be taken to ensure compatibility.
Public nuisance mosquito control will be authorized annually by Special Use Permit.
Permit conditions will stipulate that all control work will be carried out in conformance with preapproved Pesticide Use Proposals and Section 7 Endangered Species consultations.
Permittee will need to notify the Refuge five days prior to spraying so that Refuge staff can collect bird use data and survey the pond area for nesting birds.
Spraying will not be allowed during the shorebird nesting season (March 15Â­August 31) if avocets or stilts are known to be incubating or if snowy plovers with chicks are utilizing the pond.
Typically, mosquito control efforts occur from December through April, early enough to avoid the snowy plover nesting season.
Snowy plovers primarily use the area around the saline pond to rear chicks.
However, there has been one treatment in the past five years where
spraying has occurred after April (in mid-June).
Therefore, the Refuge will monitor the proposed spray area and will not allow spraying where snowy plovers occur due to potential disturbance from the helicopter.
Bti and methoprene are not toxic to plants, lepidopterans, or birds.
Even small amounts of drift should not adversely effect these plants or animals.
Mosquito abatement practices cause temporary disturbances to wildlife.
If the applicator follows the stipulations outlined in the Special Use Permit, mosquito abatement will not harm listed species.
Western snowy plover breeding activities on the Refuge and throughout the Monterey Bay area will continue to be monitored by Point Reyes Bird Observatory (PRBO).
PRBO will monitor and document western snowy plover use of the Refuge and document causes of mortality and disturbance.
Other threatened and endangered species and Refuge resources will also be monitored by Refuge staff.
Terms and conditions of the Special Use Permit will be subject to annual modification if disturbance is considered to interfere with or detract from the fulfillment of the purpose of the Refuge.
For example, if bird surveys determine that an unacceptable level of flushing or disturbance occurs during helicopter treatment, only hand application will be allowed.
Golden Bear will be used as a last resort if Bti and methoprene are proven ineffective.
Justification: Fish and Wildlife Service policy provides for the control of pest species, provided that: (1) the pest organism represents a threat to human health and well-being or private property, the acceptable level of damage by the pest has been exceeded, or State or local governments have designated that pest as noxious; (2) the pest organism is detrimental to primary objectives; (3) the planned control program will not conflict with attainment of Refuge objectives or the purposes for which the Refuge is managed; and (4) The Service is currently developing new national policy regarding mosquito control on refuges.
This compatibility determination will be reviewed once the new policy is finalized.
Mosquito abatement practices cause significant but temporary disturbances to wildlife.
However, the number of treatment days per year is low, and if the applicator follows the stipulations necessary to ensure compatibility, mosquito abatement practices are determined to be compatible.
Should further biological monitoring of this activity document a substantial prolonged reduction of bird use, or direct destruction of shorebird nests, this determination will be reanalyzed on the basis of the new data.
At that time, mosquito control may be authorized by Special Use Permit only during emergency
situations based on a demonstrated public health concern, based on the presence of human diseaseÂ­bearing viruses in mosquitos in the vicinity of the Refuge.
