Delegation of Authority - Guidelines for Mitigating the Effects of Fire Suppression LINE BUILDING 1.
2.
Do not fall snags on the outside of the line unless they are an obvious safety hazard.
On the inside of the line, fall only those snags that would reach the fire line should they burn and fall over, or if they are an obvious safety hazard.
45
3.
4.
5.
Don't cut live trees over 12" d.b.h. unless deemed absolutely necessary by the Complex Manager.
Limbing of these trees, as necessary, should be the first choice.
Cut brush or small trees flush with the ground if the area is visible from roads.
Lop and scatter cut limbs so the depth will not exceed 15 inches.
MOP-UP 1.
2.
3.
Extinguish fire in living trees or snags within 200 feet of the fires perimeter with water or dirt.
Fell those trees as a last resort.
If felling occurs in the vicinity of service roads/trails, cut the stumps flush with the ground.
Buck fallen trees across service roads/trails only to the extent necessary to facilitate road/trail passage.
AIR OPERATIONS 1.
2.
Consider fixed wing delivery of water vs. standard colored retardant.
When possible, use long line slings instead of cutting helispots.
